Text.Value: You what?! But she was immortal. How could she... how could you...?
I couldn't tell her who I was. I had to protect them - and myself - no matter what.
I found Last Light within the shadows. Made a shelter there. Prayed my father wouldn't find me.
But I admit that plays second fiddle to helping you. None of us will be safe until the horror behind 'the Absolute' is defeated. When the time comes, I'll fight at your side.
When an emissary of Sel√ªne came to our little town, we were elated. Dame Aylin. Daughter of the Moonmaiden herself.
Perhaps there's something I can do to help the fight against the Dead Three. The moon is rather good at illuminating darkness, after all.
Ketheric Thorm is - was - my father.
A great deal, but still some of the details elude me.
You jest, yet he did seem a ghost to me. A shadow of the father I loved. He resurrected me with magic so foul I nearly retch just thinking of it.
She's a formidable woman, my Aylin, but no one could escape such horrors unscathed. She's in my hands, now, and I intend to help her through whatever's to come.
You and Aylin seem to have a lot of history. What happened?
It's too late for that. We killed her.
Ketheric captured her and was using her to fuel his invulnerability. She was called the 'Nightsong'.
It's too late for that. I killed her.
In seriousness, my home needs me. It's still enveloped in Shar's horrific curse. If it can be cleansed, I'll find a way.
Why would you lie? What's the matter with you?
No, but it sounds like you do.
I know you'll look out for her. You will, right? Of course you will.
On my life, I wouldn't go near magic so vile.
By the time Jaheira came, I'd pieced together just enough to know I'd been dead a hundred years. That my father was the source of the horrors plaguing this land - my home.
I did. Who would trust the next-of-kin of Ketheric Thorm? But I have no more secrets.
And a monster he'd become. A Myrkulite.
What will you do now that your father's gone?
Not on purpose. Or not with the intent to deceive. I've been trying to make sense of it all.
Liar. Wicked, wicked liar. Murderer.
As I was saying, I fell in love with Aylin swiftly. It was as easy as breathing.
I should hope so. I can't imagine what insane course of thought led you to murder someone so dear.
In seriousness, I intend to help you fight the Absolute - what lies behind the Absolute, that is.
Look after my angel, of course. She's been through more than I can bear to think about.
It seems there's a great deal you haven't told me.
Get out of my sight before I do something you'll regret.
Then - and this is where I still need answers - I died. I'm not sure how. Why. But all was black, black, black.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hesitatntly, still trying to figure things out

Text.Value: So you're Ketheric's daughter. Where were you while he was amassing an army for the Absolute?
A mission? A mission?! That Sharran murderer destroyed someone so precious, so good...
Leave.
Love? Eh. Lust? Hourly.
You really claim to be unaware of his doings?
Nightsong? What do you mean?
I certainly believe you were starstruck, at least.
Leave.
Guilty. The moment I looked at Aylin, I just knew I had to be with her. I was hers. That was it.
This was different. It was like I could see my fate in her eyes.
Lucky for me, she felt the same way. But my father was sceptical. Aylin is immortal, after all.
Shar got the better of me. It won't happen again.
She... what?! Does this mean she's still alive? I've got to find her - set her free! Tell me everything you know. Please.
It was the only way to make Ketheric vulnerable.
Without you, we'd be there still. My father fell so far from light, the shadow of him nearly swallowed us all whole.
Tell me, do you believe in love at first sight?
There is. But perhaps it's time you knew the entire truth.
I'm grateful for your help - your friendship. I hope we won't intrude on your hospitality too long, but I'm grateful for a safe place to... well, just to be.
So you're Ketheric's daughter. Where were you while he was amassing an army for the Absolute?
By killing him, you set him free. You set Aylin free. And me.
It's... a long story. But I'll tell it - you deserve to know.
It's all out in the open now. And with my father dead, I have nothing to fear. Only his wicked legacy to undo.
Never mind.
We'll both of us stand by you when the time comes to put down the horror that threatens this city. We are your allies for life.
That's what Ketheric and his chums called her. Killed her myself.
It's too late for that. She was dead when I found her.
Are you like him? A Myrkulite?
Aylin - do you mean Nightsong?
I couldn't hold my companion back. She had a mission to fulfil.
Oh it won't? Then I suppose we'll just forget this little misstep, file it under 'lessons learned'?
I hope Aylin's all right. Can't wait to have her in my arms again...
That's what Ketheric and his chums called her. We killed her.
I'd like to know what happened between you and your father Ketheric.
Why did you lie about who you are?
You really claim to be unaware of his doings?
My father raised me to serve Sel√ªne, as my mother, rest her soul, had wished. He was everything to me, all my life.
And my father... I heard what happened - what he'd become.
That's exactly it. And I tell you, I took one look at her, and I just knew. She was it.
I feel there's a great deal you haven't told me.
Keeping very well, I hope?
You did it - you killed him. Ketheric Thorm. My... my father.
Leave.
I mourn the man I knew. He was... wonderful.
Leave.
Thank you - thank you so much. I'll gather some supplies and head out shortly. Aylin... I can't believe she's alive. Before the day's end, I'll have her in my arms. Incredible.
It was a mistake. One I bitterly regret.
Give me your map. I'll show you where she's being kept.
I understand it's... strange. There's an imbalance between us, certainly. But I suppose loving Aylin felt the same as loving myself. It was natural.
Looking forward to a bit of rest, if I'm honest. It's been a long century.
He'd become the Chosen of Myrkul.
As you know, Ketheric Thorm is - was - my father.
It's all out in the open now. And with my father dead, I have nothing to fear. Except for Aylin. She needs healing. Rest.
I didn't know that then. But I could see the change in him. He told me we'd be together now, said Aylin was dead. I couldn't speak. Could only run.
Oh, I don't know. Change my hair colour. Buy a horse.

EditorData.NodeContext: Kidding, but she's not a natural jokester so she's a little awkward

Text.Value: Tell me again about what happened between you and your father Ketheric.
You what?! But she was immortal. How could she... how could you...? She is the Moonmaiden's daughter. And you call yourself a Sel√ªnite?!
Did he shout 'boo!'?
What will you do now that your father's gone?
Next I knew, I was being jolted awake. I smelled musty air. I saw shadows. And then my father's face, so changed, so hideously warped.
When we met, it was like a lightning strike. My father wasn't sure about us - she was immortal, after all - but I never doubted.
Get away from me. Now.
Leave.
You did it - you killed him. Ketheric Thorm. My... my father.
A hundred years in the Shadowfell. A hundred years being murdered by Sharrans over and over. It fills me with a rage I can hardly contain.
You and Aylin seem to have a lot of history. What happened?
He's gone now. But I suppose the man I knew died when I died. The man he became - that wasn't the father I knew. The one I loved so very much.
I had a safe haven - it was my duty to protect the people at Last Light. If I'd told them I was the daughter of Ketheric Thorm, they might've taken their chances in the darkness.
My father said she was gone. I'd tried to make my peace with it. But... she was so special. So very dear.
I can't believe it. I can't believe Aylin is here.
I wish Aylin would be more careful. I couldn't bear to lose her again.

EditorData.logicalname: NS is going to Ramazith but no situation resolve yet

Text.Value: You're disgusting. You've killed someone so precious, so good. I knew Shar was wicked. But I'd hoped for better from you.
He raised me to serve Sel√ªne, as my mother, rest her soul, had wished. He was everything to me, all my life.
When the Lady of Loss speaks, her faithful act on her behalf.
Only a monster would rip his own daughter from the grave.
You sound like my father. But it was more than that. This was no mere attraction - it was love.
I had no idea what he'd become until it was too late. I fled from him when I found out - kept a sanctuary in the shadows, where I met Jaheira.
Understandable.
By the time Jaheira came, I'd pieced together just enough to know I'd been dead a hundred years. That my father was the source of the horrors that plagued my home.
So you lied about who you were.
Aren't you at all sad about your father's fate?
He told me we'd be together now, said Aylin was dead. I couldn't speak. Could only run.
Was it? Was it truly? I don't believe that. Not for a second.
Certainly. There's magic in a look.
None of us will be safe until that looming horror is defeated. When the time comes, I'll fight at your side.
You're lying. She can't be saved, can she? My father told me she was... gone. It's true, isn't it?

Synopsis: Isobel is hanging out in MOO after the defeat of Ketheric. If NS is alive, this dialogue will follow their reunion. She is glad Ketheric is dead and does exposition about her story with her father/ Nightsong. At the end she may join your camp.
